{
  "response_text": "Average weekly consumption of skimmed and semi-skimmed milk begins at approximately 5.3 units per agent, reflecting the historical market dominance of whole milk in the initial time period corresponding to 1974. Over the first ten to eleven time steps, consumption increases rapidly and significantly, reaching approximately 1,265 units by step 11. This initial surge indicates a swift disposition triggering phase where agents begin considering alternatives, driven by perception of health characteristics and early social influence effects within the Watts-Strogatz network topology.\n\nFollowing this rapid adoption phase, the system enters a prolonged plateau period spanning roughly steps 12 through 24, where consumption oscillates between approximately 1,183 and 1,265 units. During this interval, the metric exhibits non-significant trends with periodic fluctuations, suggesting a stabilization period where habit formation and cognitive dissonance mechanisms create resistance to further change. Local peaks occur around steps 11, 13, 19, and 21, interspersed with valleys at steps 12, 18, 20, and 23, indicating ongoing dynamic tension between social influence promoting adoption and incumbent habit strength maintaining existing behaviors.\n\nFrom step 25 onward, consumption resumes a significant increasing trend, climbing from approximately 1,220 units to a final value of 1,456.6 units by step 32. This late-stage growth reflects the gradual erosion of initial habit strength as social norms consolidate and agents adjust their choice functions through post-choice evaluation mechanisms. Throughout the simulation, variance across runs remains relatively contained, with all 30 matched series following similar S-curve diffusion patterns characterized by early acceleration, middle-period oscillation, and late-stage convergence toward widespread adoption of alternative milk varieties."
}

